{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_88","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"nl -ba docs/experiment_orchestration_notes/FW-M15-007_rationale.md | sed -n '1,240p'\"","aggregated_output":"     1\t# FW-M15-007 Rationale\n     2\t\n     3\t## Design Choices\n     4\t\n     5\tThis ticket adds one suite-owned reporting module,\n     6\t`flywire_wave.experiment_suite_reporting`, plus a thin CLI wrapper\n     7\t`scripts/33_suite_report.py`.\n     8\t\n     9\tThe key design choice is to keep reporting downstream of the existing Milestone\n    10\t15 package and aggregation layers instead of introducing a third discovery\n    11\tmechanism.\n    12\t\n    13\t- the workflow accepts `experiment_suite_package.json` or `result_index.json`\n    14\t- it recomputes suite aggregation from the packaged suite inventory\n    15\t- it generates plots, catalogs, and the offline HTML review surface only from\n    16\t  the packaged inventory and suite rollups\n    17\t- it does not reopen raw per-experiment directories or re-infer comparisons\n    18\t  from folder structure\n    19\t\n    20\tThat preserves the boundary from `FW-M15-005` and `FW-M15-006`: package first,\n    21\taggregate second, report third.\n    22\t\n    23\tThe review output stays intentionally static and local.\n    24\t\n    25\t- `package/aggregation/` remains the stable home for machine-friendly rollups\n    26\t  and CSV exports\n    27\t- `package/report/suite_review/` now adds a deterministic reviewer surface with\n    28\t  `index.html`, `suite_review_summary.json`, `catalog/artifact_catalog.json`,\n    29\t  and generated SVG plots\n    30\t- plots get JSON sidecars that record source table identity, source pairing\n    31\t  ids, suite-cell ids, bundle ids, and source paths\n    32\t\n    33\tThat is enough for fast local review without pretending this first version is a\n    34\tweb app.\n    35\t\n    36\tAnother deliberate choice is to keep the review surface visibly sectioned along\n    37\tthe same boundaries already established in earlier tickets:\n    38\t\n    39\t- `shared_comparison_metrics` is the fairness-critical surface\n    40\t- `wave_only_diagnostics` is explicitly separate\n    41\t- `validation_findings` is explicitly separate\n    42\t\n    43\tThe HTML report, plot directories, and artifact catalog all preserve that\n    44\tseparation so reviewers do not have to guess which outputs are safe to compare\n    45\tdirectly against baseline-driven claims.\n    46\t\n    47\tI also chose deterministic SVG generation over notebook code or a heavier\n    48\tplotting stack.\n    49\t\n    50\t- SVG files are plain-text, diffable, and path-stable\n    51\t- labels come directly from normalized suite/group/metric identity rather than\n    52\t  hand-written captions\n    53\t- reruns overwrite the same files with the same ordering, legend labels, and\n    54\t  axis labels\n    55\t\n    56\tThat keeps the first Milestone 15 review surface honest and repeatable.\n    57\t\n    58\t## Testing Strategy\n    59\t\n    60\tThe regression coverage stays fixture-driven and reuses the real packaged-suite\n    61\tsmoke boundary.\n    62\t\n    63\t`tests/test_experiment_suite_reporting.py`:\n    64\t\n    65\t- materializes the representative packaged suite fixture from the aggregation\n    66\t  test workflow\n    67\t- runs the new reporting API against packaged suite metadata\n    68\t- reruns the same workflow and asserts deterministic summary payloads\n    69\t- verifies that the static HTML, summary JSON, and artifact catalog are written\n    70\t- checks at least one suite summary-table export and one generated comparison\n    71\t  plot\n    72\t- validates expected section separation, plot labels, table metadata, and plot\n    73\t  traceability back to pairings and bundle references\n    74\t- compares one generated SVG across reruns to ensure label/content stability\n    75\t\n    76\tThat test intentionally targets the same packaged-suite contract that a human\n    77\treviewer will use, rather than a hand-built fake artifact catalog.\n    78\t\n    79\t## Simplifications\n    80\t\n    81\tThe first version stays conservative in a few places.\n    82\t\n    83\t- report generation reruns the aggregation workflow instead of caching a second\n    84\t  incremental state layer\n    85\t- plots are deterministic grouped-bar SVGs, not interactive notebooks or a\n    86\t  richer client-side plotting system\n    87\t- the artifact catalog records traceability metadata, but it does not revise\n    88\t  the suite-package contract to register the new report outputs as package-owned\n    89\t  contract artifacts\n    90\t- the HTML report previews summary-table rows and links to CSVs rather than\n    91\t  embedding full table explorers\n    92\t- validation plots summarize finding-count deltas only; they do not yet render\n    93\t  a validator-by-validator diff matrix\n    94\t\n    95\tThese choices bias toward one boring, inspectable reporting workflow instead of\n    96\ttrying to solve full review UX in one ticket.\n    97\t\n    98\t## Future Expansion Points\n    99\t\n   100\tThe clearest next steps are:\n   101\t\n   102\t- register suite-review outputs into a later suite-package contract revision if\n   103\t  stronger discovery guarantees become necessary\n   104\t- add richer validation visuals keyed by validator family, finding identity, or\n   105\t  status transition\n   106\t- add optional plot filtering for metric families, ablation families, or\n   107\t  dimension slices\n   108\t- add compact HTML table sorting/filtering if reviewers need more interactive\n   109\t  local inspection without moving to a service\n   110\t- extend SVG plotting with confidence intervals or additional summary-statistic\n   111\t  overlays if later rollups expose those semantics explicitly\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_89","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'nl -ba docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md | tail -n 80'","aggregated_output":"   168\t  review artifacts under a suite-owned root, but it must keep the role IDs,\n   169\t  lineage semantics, and upstream bundle references frozen here\n   170\t\n   171\tThat keeps this ticket from pre-empting the later packaging work while still\n   172\tlocking the suite vocabulary now.\n   173\t\n   174\t## Ownership Boundary\n   175\t\n   176\tThe boundary is explicit:\n   177\t\n   178\t- Jack owns suite identity, dimension IDs, artifact roles, lineage semantics,\n   179\t  work-item status semantics, and reproducibility mechanics\n   180\t- Grant owns which scientifically meaningful ablation families, parameter\n   181\t  choices, and subset choices are declared through that surface\n   182\t\n   183\tIn other words:\n   184\t\n   185\t- Jack owns how the suite is described and replayed\n   186\t- Grant owns which scientific perturbations are worth describing through it\n   187\t\n   188\t## Reproducibility Semantics\n   189\t\n   190\t`experiment_suite.v1` freezes these first reproducibility hooks:\n   191\t\n   192\t- `suite_spec_hash`\n   193\t- `suite_cell_id`\n   194\t- `parent_lineage_reference`\n   195\t- `simulation_seed_scope`\n   196\t- `ablation_seed_scope`\n   197\t- `artifact_reference_catalog`\n   198\t- `stable_discovery_order`\n   199\t\n   200\tInvariants:\n   201\t\n   202\t- suite discovery is metadata-backed rather than directory-scan-backed\n   203\t- suite-cell identity is independent of output file naming\n   204\t- simulator seed lineage stays separate from ablation perturbation lineage\n   205\t- later suite tables and plots must point back to metadata-backed bundle\n   206\t  references rather than becoming a second source of truth\n   207\t\n   208\t## Consequences For Later Milestone 15 Tickets\n   209\t\n   210\tLater Milestone 15 work may add:\n   211\t\n   212\t- suite-manifest normalization\n   213\t- deterministic suite expansion and execution\n   214\t- ablation transform realizations\n   215\t- suite packaging and indexing\n   216\t- suite aggregation, tables, plots, and reports\n   217\t\n   218\tThose tickets should reuse the IDs, lineage kinds, work-item statuses, artifact\n   219\troles, and reproducibility hooks frozen here. If they need different meanings,\n   220\tthat is a new contract version rather than a silent edit to\n   221\t`experiment_suite.v1`.\n   222\t\n   223\t## Local Review Workflow\n   224\t\n   225\tThe first deterministic local review workflow now has two explicit steps after a\n   226\tsuite has been executed and packaged:\n   227\t\n   228\t1. `scripts/32_suite_aggregation.py` consumes the packaged suite inventory and\n   229\t   writes suite-level JSON plus CSV rollups under `package/aggregation/`\n   230\t2. `scripts/33_suite_report.py` consumes the packaged suite inventory again,\n   231\t   regenerates aggregation deterministically, and writes reviewer-facing report\n   232\t   artifacts under `package/report/suite_review/`\n   233\t\n   234\tThe review directory contains:\n   235\t\n   236\t- `index.html`: static offline suite review surface\n   237\t- `suite_review_summary.json`: deterministic summary metadata\n   238\t- `catalog/artifact_catalog.json`: table, plot, and report discovery catalog\n   239\t- `plots/<section-id>/*.svg`: auto-generated comparison plots with stable labels\n   240\t\n   241\tThat workflow is intentionally metadata-backed and local:\n   242\t\n   243\t- it starts from `experiment_suite_package.json` or `result_index.json`\n   244\t- it does not reparse raw per-experiment directories\n   245\t- it keeps `shared_comparison_metrics`, `wave_only_diagnostics`, and\n   246\t  `validation_findings` visibly separate in both the catalog and the HTML\n   247\t  report\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
